The PI led a group of postdocs, Ph.D. students and collaborators from Havard School of Public Health, Yale University, and Penn Medical School  to develop a comprehensive theory and methodology for high-dimensional statistical inference and applications in genomics and engineering during the grant period (8/2009-7/2013).  The PI's major activities and achievements are summarized as follows. 


1. edited 2 books and published 45 journal papers including more than 30 papers in top statistics and engineering journals such as the Annals of Statistics, Journal of the American Statistical Association, Journal of the Royal Statistical Society, Biometrika, and IEEE Transactions on Information Theory;

2. trained 5 postdocs and 2 Ph.D. students, including 1 female postdoc and 2 female students, all of whom have taken up research faculty positions;

3. gave 18 plenary/distinguished lectures and 20 invited talks at professional conferences on research supported by the FRG grant, including Distinguished Lecture at the 2nd IMS Asia Pacific Rim Meeting in Tokyo, Japan, the Forum Lecture at the 28th European Meeting of Statisticians, plenary talk at the International Conference on High Dimensional Statistics in Singapore, the Hermann Otto Hirschfeld Lectures at Humboldt-Universit&auml;t zu Berlin, Keynote Lecture at the International Conference on Statistics and Optimization in Beijing, China, and the Plenary Lecture at the 7th annual Information Theory and Applications Conference in San Diego.

4. co-organized 5 international conferences/workshops on high-dimensional statistical inference and its applications; (i). 'Random Matrices and High Dimensional Statistics' at the IMA in Minnesota in April 2011; (iii). 'NSF Workshop on High Dimensional Data' in Nantucket, Massachusetts in May2011; (iii). 'NSF Workshop for High-Dimensional Data: Theory, Methodology and Applications' at Yale in June 2012. In addition, the PI co-organized an Oberwolfach workshop in Germany in March 2012 and an international conference in June 2013 in Beijing, China.These workshops/conferences brought together statisticians, probabilists, engineers, and computer scientists to advance the theory, methodology and applications of high-dimensional inference. The workshops also provided opportunities for scholars from diverse disciplines to interact and strengthen each other's knowledge and expertise in analyzing high-dimensional data to yield maximal new knowledge toward the establishment of rigorous mathematical and biological foundations for the better understanding of health and disease. The workshop attracted graduate students, postdoctoral fellows as well as junior faculty members to be involved with this exciting area of research;

5. organized a special seminar series at Penn dedicated to high dimensional inference. The talks covered a range of topics, including the theory, methods and applications of high dimensional inference. The seminar series was well attended by the faculty and graduate students;

6. taught a special topics course on high dimensional inference to advanced graduate students and postdocs in fall, 2009.


All the papers and related software packages were made freely available on the PI's website and the workshops/conferences co-organized by the PI were well attended by scientists from related fields, including engineering and medicine.

